Prolagus is an extinct genus of pika within the order Lagomorpha, (which also includes the Leporidae (rabbits and hares). It was previously considered a member of the monotypic family Prolagidae.Prolagus first appeared in the Early Miocene in Europe, where it ranged widely for most of the period, by the Middle Pleistocene it was confined to Sardinia where it survived until historical times. In Africa and Asia, the genus is known from the Miocene and Pliocene. The scientific name may mean "before hares" or "primitive hares" (pro- meaning "before" and lagos meaning "hare").